hool, psychiatry, and founded a heralded mental health center in PA. Children should have the right to choose, once they reach a certain age, to attend school. VA is extreme in having no accountability for parents to show their children are getting the basics; while not many in the US, there are some families where parents are so rigidly attached to their beliefs that children have no freedoms at all. These can be Christian, Muslim, any faith--it's the rigidity that's the problem. The idea that you can control your children and their minds is just delusional, and more often than not leads to rebellion, acting out, runaways, and the like. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="953" language="en" documentId="317" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Whiteguy for diversity" date="7/29/2013 3:58 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375106323-527-463" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="317" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="953"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>